<mailto:andrew.coenen@gmail.com|andrew.coenen@gmail.com> - please email me at any time if you want to learn more! And I'd appreciate it more than anything if you let me know what you've been up to!

Alright y'all! Today's the last class and I wanted to let you know how proud I am to have had you all as students. It's really amazing how far you've come in such a short amount of time, and I'm incredibly excited to see what you get into next. As far as good follow-up material goes, my favorite javascript resource out there is Eloquent Javascript, available free here: <http://eloquentjavascript.net/> - this book has, in my opinion, the best way of teaching more advanced JS / programming subject matter and is an extremely invaluable resource for preparing for galvanize's coding bootcamp, if you're interested!

And if so, I highly recommend applying as soon as you can. There's no better time than the present, and being able to use the knowledge you've gained in this class as a springboard to next steps is an awesome way to keep gaining momentum as programmers!

Anyway, once again, it's been a huge privilege to get to teach you all even just the tiniest slice of what it is to build things on the web. It's an incredibly rewarding line of work that's made only better by sharing with others. So thanks so much!

messages.text: Thank you for sharing your knowledge!

hey all, I didn't realize it before but by putting due dates on the previous assignments it prevented anyone who may have missed the deadline from submitting their work later. Anyway, in the interest of making sure everyone has a chance to do all of the <http://repl.it|repl.it> assignments, I've removed due dates from all previous and outstanding assignments, and won't be putting them on any longer. This'll allow anyone who wants/needs to catch up / redo their work to do so! 

Just wanna say too that I'm so happy to have all of you in the class, and I couldn't be happier with your progress so far. Just think, last monday you'd never touched JS code and this week you'll be writing real, actual, working programs. It really is amazing! And just remember, the struggle is part of the process - you're gonna learn a million times more having it be kinda hard and overwhelming at times than if it were all smooth sailing.

Best of luck, and see you on Monday! Happy coding!
